image.altText: close up of side of Scott Morrison's face

props.synopsis: Former prime minister Scott Morrison said he wanted a woman to replace him in the very safe seat of Cook. What happened instead has been described as "blatant, arrogant and overt" — a concerted campaign driven by some of the country's most influential figures.

title.children: A prime minister's seat up for grabs, the backlash in the battle for Cook

image.altText: Bruce Lehrmann defamation case

props.synopsis: Bruce Lehrmann is likely to be left millions of dollars in debt as he gets the bill today for his failed defamation action against Network Ten and journalist Lisa Wilkinson.

title.children: Bruce Lehrmann likely to receive bill for millions over failed defamation case

image.altText: A still from a video showing a confrontation between two men standing up as others watch on.

props.synopsis: An ABC investigation uncovers a series of allegations by former workers blowing the whistle on mistreatment, neglect and excessive use of force against people with disabilities being cared for by NDIS provider Evolution Support Services.

title.children: Jake's support worker tells him to settle down. Seconds later, there's a sickening crack and a cry of pain

image.altText: A woman wearing a hijab standing in a doorway

props.synopsis: Community legal centres are braced for a slashing of their government funding and fear it will leave those who rely on their services at risk of violence and homelessness.

title.children: Free legal centres say without more government funding vulnerable people will slip through the cracks

image.altText: A young man with brown hair, with blonde highlight at the tips, and a grey knit looking at the camera.

props.synopsis: The 1998 death of Matthew Shepard, and trial of his killers, inspired the play, The Laramie Project. Now, a single performance of the play will begin in Sydney next week.

title.children: The Laramie Project will soon be in Sydney, mirroring the city's own history with homophobic killings

image.altText: Don Bradman's childhood home is for sale

props.synopsis: The house that helped shape the world's best-ever batsman has been put on the market after 17 years by its current owner, who completed a meticulous restoration project.

title.children: 134 years not out, Don Bradman's restored childhood home goes on the market

image.altText: Two fluffy white puppies lying on the grass.

props.synopsis: An animal sanctuary is receiving up to five phone calls a day from dog owners asking, 'Can you take my Maremma?' as they find the bundles of fluff become large dogs needing lots of room and discipline.

title.children: Why these cute, fluffy dogs are creating a Maremma dilemma and surrendered by unsuspecting families

image.altText: Two men stand together with their arms around each other

props.synopsis: Disappearances are not uncommon in Mexico. But in their haste to close the case of murdered surfers Jake and Callum Robinson and Carter Rhoad, local authorities have left a lot of questions unanswered.

title.children: Jake and Callum Robinson's deaths have raised questions over cartel involvement. A former detective explains why

image.altText: A sign on the edge of a sports ground. It has been vandalised.

props.synopsis: The former Test cricketer is facing of domestic violence and residents in his hometown of Wagga Wagga say it's time to consider renaming the ground.

title.children: Vandalism of sign at Michael Slater Oval sparks calls for ground to be renamed

image.altText: A orange ship tied up in port.

props.synopsis: A Senate inquiry into funding issues at the Australian Antarctic Division releases its final report, which calls for Australia to consider a second resupply vessel to ensure the significant scientific capabilities of the nation's trouble-plagued icebreaker are not wasted.

title.children: Antarctic inquiry calls for second vessel to complement Nuyina, blasts division's 'bewildering' budget overspend

image.altText: A hand holding a bacterial agar plate is inside a clear screen

props.synopsis: Matthew donates poo to his local stool bank to help treat gut diseases. In the future, faecal transplants may use gut bacteria grown in the lab, not in humans.

title.children: Unlocking the code of the 'super pooper' could usher in new wave of gut health treatments

image.altText: A man in a white long-sleeved t-shirt is escorted by two police officers while in handcuffs outside a police station.

props.synopsis: The man charged over the alleged stabbing of a woman in the car park of a gym in Sydney's inner south was previously given an 18-month  intensive corrections order for twice breaching an AVO.

title.children: Man charged over alleged stabbing of woman outside gym twice breached AVO, court records show

image.altText: Coffs creek walkway facing east

props.synopsis: Police have ramped up patrols in Coffs Harbour after a 45-year-old woman was attacked on a popular walking track, just days after the region was rocked by a murder and a violent robbery.

title.children: Woman bashed, left unconscious beside walkway in third violent attack in a week in coastal city

image.altText: Two women look at a share price board outside the ASX in Sydney.

props.synopsis: The Bank of England holds interest rates steady but the governor is "optimistic" about interest rate cuts while US indices lift, continuing a strong run. Follow the day's events and insights from our business reporters on the ABC News live markets blog.

title.children: Wall Street keeps lifting, Bank of England holds rates steady and ASX set to rise

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: ASX set to rise after Wall Street lifts

image.altText: View of the High Court of Australia sign in Canberra.

props.synopsis: A judgement is due in the case of an Iranian man refusing to be deported, and it could lead to many more immigration detainees being released.

title.children: Judgement day comes for High Court immigration case that could cause more headaches for federal government

image.altText: A woman with blonde hair standing in a green paddock, holding a framed photo of a man.

props.synopsis: Patrick Liedke, 39, was last seen west of Tweed Heads on April 22. His car was found on April 26 on a property nearby. His sister has strong hopes he is still out there.

title.children: Family of missing man rallies team of volunteers to help find him after police call off search

image.altText: Adam Bandt

props.synopsis: The federal Greens are calling for Israel's ambassador to Australia to be expelled, as Israel prepares an invasion of the southern Gaza city of Rafah.

title.children: Greens call for Israeli ambassador's expulsion over looming Rafah invasion

image.altText: A white, green and blue Air Vanuatu plane in the sky above the blue Pacific ocean

props.synopsis: Australian tourists are stranded in Vanuatu after the country's national airline cancelled international flights for four days, while the Vanuatu government considers putting it into voluntary administration.

title.children: Australians stranded in Vanuatu as national airline teeters on the brink of voluntary administration

image.altText: A Palestinian man stands looking through a opening in a building, watching as smoke rises after Israeli strikes.

props.synopsis: The US acknowledges its 2,000-pound bombs cause civilian deaths in Gaza and will pause supply on a shipment of the heavy weapons to Israel over concerns about their use in Rafah.

title.children: 'Powerful symbolic move': What we know about the US halt on heavy bomb supplies to Israel

image.altText: A composite image showing a variety of book covers set on an angle against a bright yellow background

props.synopsis: The Australian Book Industry Awards recognise the talented authors and publishers behind the books that generated the most buzz in the last 12 months.

title.children: Aussie retailers tried to ban this kids book. Now it's a winner at the 2024 book industry awards

image.altText: A young girl is silhouetted against fading evening sun holding a football in one hand while walking across sand dune ridge

props.synopsis: In the shadow of Uluru, an unprecedented football carnival was quietly held for young First Nations women from remote communities. More than sport was at play.

title.children: In the shadow of Uluru, the most remarkable football carnival you've never heard of tried to change history

image.altText: A woman, a group of boys, and men in a gym.

props.synopsis: Self-defence instructor Jeff Phillips is teaching young people how to defend themselves from knife crime. His phone has been running hot since the Bondi Junction attack.

title.children: Knife crime has dominated the headlines but the stats in NSW tell a different story

image.altText: Matildas goalie Lydia Williams poses for a portrait in a black jersey. She is looking into the distance with her arms crossed.

props.synopsis: Matildas goalkeeper Lydia Williams says she will retire from international football after the 2024 Paris Olympics.

title.children: 'It's been a wonderful ride': Matildas longest-serving player Lydia Williams announces retirement

image.altText: Anthony Albanese at a press conference at Parliament House

props.synopsis: Another high-profile immigration decision and a rocky relationship with China are likely the last things the prime minister wants to be talking about ahead of the Federal Budget release next week.

title.children: With China tensions boiling again and a high court decision looming, the PM's pre-budget week is anything but

image.altText: Troy SMith

props.synopsis: Bali authorities confirm an Australian man has been arrested and charged with drug offences.

title.children: Australian man arrested and charged for alleged drug offences in Bali

image.altText: Split screen of Kate Thwaites, Michele Ananda-Rajah, Sally Sitou and Jerome Laxale side by side

props.synopsis: Labor backbenchers say they were caught off guard by the government's new gas policy, which the resources minister says will keep the fossil fuel in Australia's energy mix until 2050 "and beyond".

title.children: Labor backbench 'blindsided' by Albanese's gas strategy that keeps fuel 'to 2050 and beyond'

image.altText: Troy Mercanti

props.synopsis: Notorious bikie Troy Mercanti is awarded costs after rape charges against him relating to an alleged incident in Karrinyup are dropped in a Perth court today.

title.children: Rape charges against Perth bikie Troy Mercanti dropped amid coercion fears for alleged victim

image.altText: A photograph of a strap protruding through the wall into the cabin of a plane, next to a seat.

props.synopsis: The Australian Transport Safety Bureau calls for vigilance, publishing a report into an incident in which a strap was left on the propeller of a plane that took off from Canberra Airport, damaging the aircraft and injuring a passenger, in 2022.

title.children: Report recommends stricter safety measures after propeller strap punctured aircraft taking off from Canberra Airport

image.altText: A helicopter lands on a warship's deck at sunset.

props.synopsis: Beijing's claim that an Australian helicopter was attempting to spy on the Chinese military has been rejected by Defence chief Angus Campbell, who insists the Seahawk was behaving "professionally" when it was targeted by flares.

title.children: Defence chief rejects China's spying accusation after flare confrontation

image.altText: A close up of Greg Lynn standing in front of a body of water near some rocks.

props.synopsis: A Supreme Court judge has told a panel of potential jurors that it will be alleged Greg Lynn shot Carol Clay and killed Russell Hill, who both went missing while camping in Victoria's High Country in 2020.

title.children: Greg Lynn allegedly shot Victorian camper, potential jurors told as murder trial begins

image.altText: A small cart exits a large tunnel in the an alpine national park

props.synopsis: Chief executive Dennis Barnes says Snowy 2.0 will be complete on time despite one of three tunnel-boring machines moving slower than expected.

title.children: Snowy Hydro boss doubles down on 2028 project timeline despite Florence the machine struggles

image.altText: A large aircraft takes off from an airport.

props.synopsis: "Bruce", the first of Bonza's repossessed 737-Max 8 aircraft, takes off from the Sunshine Coast to an unknown overseas destination after negotiations to keep the budget airline in the air failed.

title.children: Bonza's aircraft leave the country after fleet repossessed
